column7: What is the state of the image, in terms of physical damage sustained?
column8: Be mindful of damage that places the image or visual information at risk. If the non-image (shinier) side of the film or border area is scuffed without clear damage to the image/emulsion side, the image may be "Good" or even "Excellent." "Good" to "Critical" can describe a range of image scratches, abrasions, or cracks. Delamination or flaking (image loss) is inherently "Serious" or "Critical", depending on the degree of irreparable emulsion loss.

column7: Is this item exhibiting mold and/or pest (insect, rodent) damage? Check all that apply
column8: Biological organisms such as mold, insects, and rodents can very easily damage collections, often irreversibly. If this item or its container seems to display pest damage or mold growth, select which (both if necessary). Click through for more information on pests and mold. Mold can stain and even weaken materials. Though mold growth can be halted, most staining is permanent. Mold will often appear as small spots, typically overlapping, patchy, and feathery at its edges. Pests will feed on a whole host of organic substances found in collections (i.e. cellulose, gelatin), eating through paper supports, media, gelatin emulsions, binding material, etc.

column7: If acetate or nitrate, what is the level of breakdown of the base?  If polyester, select "No deterioration"
column8: Acetate and nitrate films will decay in very different ways. Click through for more information on the levels of film base decay. If you think this film is polyester, or it displays none of the typical acetate or nitrate decay characteristics, select "No deterioration".

column7: Assess the degree of image fading, discoloration, and/or staining
column8: Determine the extent to which the image material has deteriorated, naturally or by external factors. Common forms of surface staining for silver gelatin photographic images include silver mirroring (metallic, bluish cast) and orange-yellow spotting (redox blemishes). Click through for more info, including examples.

column7: Is the image clearly comprised of yellow/magenta/cyan or is there an overall red-orange tint?
column8: Chromogenic components and dye stability improved over time, most notably in 1947, when color stability and saturation was resolved by the addition of red-orange masking to the color negative. Up to that point, the negative image visibly comprised a complementary color set (yellow, magenta, and cyan). As a color negative's fading is nearly impossible to assess, we ask this question to determine the potential for image degradation.

column7: Was this negative likely manufactured before the early 1980s?
column8: To identify the manufacture era of the negative, consider both the content of the image as well as the markings/codes along the edge. Making an educated guess is fine for this particular question. Like chromogenic prints, negatives prior to the 1980s may discolor as a result of severe thermal fading of the cyan dye and poor storage in high temperatures.

column7: Identify the binder material (gelatin, collodion, albumen), if possible
column8: Albumen image tone ranges from ocher-orange to olive green, appearing creamy in dark areas, typically made with thick, irregularly sized rough-cut glass. Corners may not be coated with emulsion. Collodion image tone ranges from warm light brown to dark brown when viewed in reflected light. Uneven thickness of collodion is often apparent at the corners. Gelatin image tones range from neutral gray to black. Unlike the others, gelatin plates were made in standard sizes from factory-cut glass (< 2mm thick). Emulsion was machine-applied, resulting in a thin, smooth, even coating which also covered the edges.If you are uncertain, select "Unsure". However, remember that this will harm the accuracy of your score.

column7: Does the emulsion side have a glass cover or is the emulsion exposed?
column8: A protective sheet of similar-sized glass will help to protect the emulsion from external threatsÑmechanical damage and environmental factors (e.g. scratches, pests). If the emulsion is cracking or delaminating, a glass cover will help to sandwich and protect the fleeing image material.

column8: Be mindful of damage that places the image or visual information at risk. column7: Is this item exhibiting mold and/or pest (insect, rodent) damage? Check all that apply
column8: Biological organisms such as mold, insects, and rodents can very easily damage collections, often irreversibly. Mold will often appear as small spots, typically overlapping, patchy, and feathery at its edges. Pests will feed on a whole host of organic substances found in collections (i.e. cellulose, gelatin), eating through paper supports, media, emulsions, binding material, etc.

column7: Is this daguerreotype in a hinged case (w/ glass cover) and/or sealed package?
column8: The silver-mercury image material of the daguerreotype is extremely sensitive. Indicate whether this daguerreotype is in a package that effectively seals the plate surface off from external threats.A secure glass-and-case "package" is crucial to protect the image from external threatsÑmechanical damage and environmental factors (e.g. abrasion, tarnishing). A daguerreotype should remain enclosed in its original case or package; however, conservators may elect to repackage a compromised case if they deem it necessary.

column7: Assess the degree of image tarnishing, darkening, and/or loss of contrast
column8: Determine the extent to which the image material has deteriorated, naturally or by external factors. Tarnishing typically results from exposure to atmosphere pollutants (an opened case packaging). This will begin as a light brown that progresses toward blue-black opaque staining along the outer edge. Over time, this staining can envelop the whole image.

column7: Is the tintype's back side exhibiting rust?
column8: Oxidation and rusting of the tinype's iron substrate can cause blistering, flaking, and total loss of the image emulsion layerÑthis is the primary  threat to tintypes. Check for signs of rust across the plate's back side.

column7: Is this tintype in a sealed package and/or hinged case?
column8: Indicate whether this tintype is in a package that effectively seals it off from external threats. The silver image is not as sensitive as that of a ambrotype or daguerreotype, but does benefit from the protection of an enclosure. Most tintypes stored loose are therefore dented, bent, or scratched up.A rigid, secure case or package helps protect the image from external threatsÑmechanical damage and environmental factors (e.g. dents, scratches, rusting). Moisture and high humidity will lead to oxidation and rusting of the iron, especially if the lacquered surface has been cracked/chipped.

The silver image may also lose contrast due to exposure to light and other atmospheric factors.

If a support's corner is dented without clear damage to the image material, the image may be "Good" or even "Excellent". "Good" to "Critical" can describe a range of image scratches, abrasions, or cracks. Platinum and palladium introduce even greater acidity to the paper support; image loss (by paper flaking, fragmenting) is inherently "Serious" or "Critical", depending on the degree of irreparability.

column8: Select the degree of the support's acidic breakdown. Discoloration (e.g. yellowing) typically precedes obvious brittle properties, showing up first along the edges. column7: Assess the degree of image fading, discoloration, and/or staining
column8: Determine the extent to which the image material has deteriorated, naturally or by external factors. Fading and discoloration of the image is uncommon as the platinum/palladium is permanent. However, due to the high acidity of the metallic image, the support is placed at risk. Deterioration of the paper will often shift the image toward a warmer tone (evident in highlights). Some localized or spot staining is also possible.If the image surface has been stored in contact with other papers, there may be signs of catalytic degradation in the form of a mirror image ÒburnedÓ into the facing paper. This staining is irreversibleÑdo not house platinum prints in direct contact with other photographic materials.

column7: Is this photo on polyester, acetate, or a resin-coated (RC) paper?
column8: Acetate: 1963Ðlate 1970s; Polyester and RC paper: late 1970sÐ2011. Polyester film is by far more common as a Silver Dye-Bleach Print support than acetate film or RC paper. Polyester is also the most stable of the bunch. If uncertain about which plastic film support you have (acetate or polyester), make an educated guess based on the era (if you are incorrect and the support has not deteriorated, this will still score higher than answering "Unsure").

column7: What is the state of the image, in terms of physical damage sustained?
column8: Be mindful of damage that places the image or visual information at risk. If a support's corner is dented without clear damage to the image/emulsion, the image may be "Good" or even "Excellent". "Good" to "Critical" can describe a range of image scratches, abrasions, or cracks. Cracking will be most evident in dark image areas (where the pigmented gelatin is thickest).Emulsion delamination, lifting, or flaking (image loss) is inherently "Serious" or "Critical", depending on the degree of irreparability. These loss details will be most prominent along image edges.

column7: Is this item exhibiting mold and/or pest (insect, rodent) damage? Check all that apply
column8: Biological organisms such as mold, insects, and rodents can very easily damage collections, often irreversibly. If this item or its container seems to display pest damage or mold growth, select which (both if necessary). Click through for more information on pests and mold. Mold can stain and even weaken materials. Though mold growth can be halted, most staining is permanent. Mold will often appear as small spots, typically overlapping, patchy, and feathery at its edges. Pests will feed on a whole host of organic substances found in collections (i.e. cellulose, gelatin), eating through paper supports, media, emulsions, binding material, etc.

column8: Select the degree of the support's acidic breakdown. Discoloration (e.g. yellowing) typically precedes obvious brittle properties, showing up first along the edges. Discoloration is usually more apparent on the back. If both yellowed and brittle, this support (cardboard or paper) is likely in an advanced stage of degradation.

column7: Is this a peel-apart or integral (e.g. type 600) instant photo?
column8: Black-and-white instant photos are generally of the peel-apart (or pack film) variety, though B&W integral photos do exist (Polaroid type 600), but are relatively rare. Integral type film will have a characteristically thicker border along the lower half (where the photo development chemical pod is). column7: Is this a peel-apart (e.g. Polacolor) or integral (e.g. SX-70) instant photo?
column8: Color instant photos may be of either the peel-apart (pack film) or integral film type. Color peel-apart photos were often packaged with self-adhesive mounts to curb curling; so these are typically rigid (and flat) or curling (and flexible), and will bear a "Polacolor" (or other manufacturer) and/or alphanumeric date code. Integral type film will have a characteristically thicker border along the lower half (where the photo development chemical pod is)Ñthis is what many associate with Polaroid's SX-70 film. Click through for examples.Common format dimensions: 3_Ó x 4_Ó (peel-apart), 3_Ó x 3_Ó (peel-apart), and 3_Ó x 4_Ó (integral).

column7: Does the image appear to be distorted or cracking?
column8: Distortion results from silver and dye image migration (likely due to poor storage orientation); cracking typically results from the photo's exposure to fluctuating relative humidity.

column8: Select the degree of the support's breakdown. Discoloration (e.g. yellowing) typically precedes obvious brittle properties, showing up first along the edges. Discoloration is usually more apparent on the back. If both yellowed and brittle, this support is likely in an advanced stage of degradation.

column7: Assess the degree of image fading, discoloration, and/or staining
column8: Determine the extent to which the image material has deteriorated, naturally or by external factors. Fading and color shifting is very common. Overall yellowing is common for integral instant photos manufactured from the 1970sÐ1980s. For peel-apart photos, the potential for discoloration is lower than that of the integral variety.
